\begin{abstract}
 Based on the Newton's second law and the Maxwell equations for the electromagnetic fields, we  establish a new  3D incompressible magneto-hydrodynamics(MHD) equations for the motion of plasma under the standard Coulomb gauge. By using the Galerkin method, we prove a result on the  existence of weak solutions for the new model.
\begin{center}
\textbf{\normalsize keywords}
\end{center}
 Maxwell equations, Plasma, Coulomb gauge, Magneto-hydrodynamics, Galerkin method.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}


It is well known that magneto-hydrodynamics is the study of the dynamics for electrically conducting fluids which are frequently generated in nature and industry, for example, the sun, beneath the Earth's mantle, plasma, liquid metals, and so on. We refer to Bittencourt's monograph [1] for the basic background and to Temam's article [11] for related mathematical issues. The  model of magneto-hydrodynamics receives an increasing attention from many authors. Such as, S. Chandrasekhar [2] first established magneto-hydrodynamic (MHD) equations. Afterwards, the extended magnetohydrodynamics (XMHD) model has been researched in high energy density (HED) plasma systems, see [10],[12],[14] and reference.


Recently, the Hall magneto-hydrodynamic (Hall-MHD) model was established by  A. Marion, D. Pierre etc in [8]. The Hall-MHD model receives an increasing attention
from plasma physicists. It is believed to be the key for understanding the problem of
magnetic reconnection. Indeed, space plasma observations provide strong evidence for the
existence of frequent and fast changes in the topology of magnetic field lines, associated to important events such as solar flares [4]. For the existence of global weak and regular solutions of the (Hall-MHD) equations, we refer to [5-7,14].

However, the above papers obtain the corresponding models by using  some approximations
and assumptions.
Motivated by the above papers, this  paper shall establish
a new three dimension  incompressible magneto-hydrodynamic equations for plasma  by some physics basic principles and we don't make any assumptions. Moreover, we give a weak  solution for the new MHD system.
\vskip 3mm
This paper is organized as follows. In Section 2 we introduce the new MHD model and also show the new MHD model is compatible with Maxwell equation. Meanwhile, we will compare the the classical MHD model and the new MHD model. In Section 3, we  give some notations, definitions and also demonstrate that a weak solution of the three dimensions incompressible MHD equations.

\section{A new governing MHD equations}
\subsection{ A new model}
The motion of plasma obey the Maxwell  Equations for electromagnetic fields
\begin{eqnarray}

\begin{aligned}
\label{21} \text{curl}\, \mathbf{E}=-\frac{\partial \mathbf{H}}{\partial t},
\end{aligned}
\\\begin{aligned}
\label{22} \text{div}\mathbf{H}=0,
\end{aligned}
\\\begin{aligned}
\label{23} \text{curl}\,\mathbf{H}=\mu_0(\mathbf{J}+\epsilon_0\frac{\partial\mathbf{E}}{\partial t}),
\end{aligned}
\\\begin{aligned}
\label{24} \text{div}\, \mathbf{E}=\frac{\rho}{\epsilon_0},
\end{aligned}
\end{eqnarray}
where $\rho,\mathbf{E},\mathbf{H},\mathbf{J},\epsilon_0$ and $\mu_0$ denote, respectively, the total charge density of the plasma, the electric field, the magnetic field, the current density, the electric permittivity, and the magnetic
permeability of free space.

Let $A_0$ be scalar potential and $\mathbf{A}=(A_1,A_2,A_3)$ be magnetic potential,  from
mathematical theory of vector fields, we get
\begin{eqnarray}

\begin{aligned}
\label{25} \mathbf{H}=\text{rot}\mathbf{A},
\end{aligned}
\\\begin{aligned}
\label{26} \mathbf{E}=-\nabla \mathbf{A_0}-\frac{\partial \mathbf{A}}{\partial t},
\end{aligned}
\\\begin{aligned}
\label{27} \text{rot}\, \mathbf{H}=\mu_0(\mathbf{J}+\epsilon_0\frac{\partial\mathbf{E}}{\partial t}),
\end{aligned}
\\\begin{aligned}\label{28}
\text{div}\, \mathbf{E}=\frac{\rho}{\epsilon_0}.
\end{aligned}
\end{eqnarray}
In other words, the system (\ref{21})-(\ref{24}) is equivalent to  (\ref{25})-(\ref{28}).



